Business/Financial Desk; Section C
ENRON'S COLLAPSE: THE OVERVIEW
Hobbled Enron Tries to Stay On Its Feet
By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr. and RIVA D. ATLAS

12/04/2001
The New York Times
Page 1, Column 2
c. 2001 New York Times Company

The Enron Corporation dismissed 4,000 employees and lined up $1.5 billion in financing yesterday to keep its main businesses on life support while it reorganizes in bankruptcy court. 
The company, once the world's largest energy trader, sought Chapter 11 protection from creditors on Sunday and is trying to conserve cash to shore up its finances.
The Justice Department has begun a criminal investigation into the company's activities, a person close to the matter said yesterday. A Justice Department spokeswoman declined to comment. The Securities and Exchange Commission is already investigating Enron's finances. 
Yesterday, Enron dismissed about half of the 7,500 employees at its headquarters in Houston and other sites scattered across the country. Before lunchtime, all employees in Houston deemed nonessential were told to go home. But on the way out, many were told that they no longer had jobs, while others were called at home and given the same message. The move follows 1,100 job cuts in Europe last week. 
The abrupt action caused fresh anger among employees, whose 401(k) retirement plans have lost $1.2 billion this year, or on average more than half their value, because of the slide in Enron's stock. 
As employees streamed out of Enron's gleaming 50-story office tower in downtown Houston, some said they were told to expect $4,500 in severance, no matter how many years of service, and to file with the bankruptcy court in New York if they wanted reimbursement for any unused vacation days. Others were told they would be informed later about severance pay and benefits. 
''Almost everyone is gone,'' said Pedro F. Manrique, a risk manager in the company's energy services division. ''Upper management is not talking. No managing directors are around, and police are on every floor. It's so unreal.'' 
Legal questions continue to multiply in what is already the largest bankruptcy in history and may well prove to be the most complex, stretching from the United States to India. 
Dynegy Inc., which Enron sued on Sunday for backing out of their merger agreement, struck back at Enron yesterday with its own lawsuit, saying that its competitor's behavior is ''one more example of Enron's failure to take responsibility for its own demise.'' Dynegy is asking the court to force Enron to transfer its crown jewel, a natural gas pipeline, to Dynegy. Dynegy's stock fell more than 10 percent yesterday, to $27.17, hitting its lowest point in intraday trading since March 2000. 
In Washington, staff members from the House Energy and Commerce Committee, which is investigating Enron's collapse, expect to discuss the matter today with the S.E.C.'s enforcement chief and general counsel. Tomorrow, they plan to meet with senior executives from Arthur Andersen, Enron's outside auditor, which has been sued by Enron shareholders and is part of the S.E.C.'s investigation into Enron's accounting troubles. And on Thursday investigators from the committee plan to fly to Houston to meet with Enron executives. 
In United States bankruptcy court in lower Manhattan, Judge Arthur J. Gonzalez said last night that he would approve the $1.5 billion financing plan for Enron after some minor changes. More than 100 lawyers overflowed the wooden benches in an overheated bankruptcy courtroom on the fifth floor of the Customs House. In a sign of how pressed the lawyers have been to respond to Enron's rapid collapse, a junior lawyer delivered the financing document more than an hour into the hearing. 
Enron secured the $1.5 billion credit line through its lead banks, J. P. Morgan Chase and Citigroup. The money, known as a debtor-in-possession financing, will provide capital to cover employees' salaries and other business functions. The Enron financing is the largest ever of this kind, according to bank analysts. 
''If we don't have it, we may need it,'' Martin J. Bienenstock, a lawyer with Weil, Gotshal & Manges, representing Enron, told the bankruptcy judge. ''If we have it, we may not have to spend it.'' 
Enron will receive $250 million immediately, and $250 million more as soon as the company provides the lenders with a satisfactory business plan. The remaining $1 billion will be used in part to repay $550 million in debts on the Transwestern Pipeline, a natural gas pipeline. 
The two banks, which together are owed about $2 billion from Enron, plan to limit their risk by selling portions of the new loan to other banks, including some lenders who currently hold Enron debt, an executive said. The credit line is secured by ''substantially all of the company's assets,'' Enron said in a statement. 
Enron is also negotiating with several large financial institutions to restart its once extensive trading floor. The aim is a joint venture with high-rated institutions, which Enron executives hope will give other energy traders confidence to resume doing business with Enron. 
But an agreement is not close at hand, executives close to the negotiations said. ''Under the best-case scenario, that would be announced at the end of the week,'' said an executive, who added that the plan could still fall through and that Enron could be forced to liquidate the trading operation. 
One of Enron's most valuable remaining assets is its largest pipeline, the Northern Natural Gas Company. Dynegy filed a lawsuit in state district court in Houston yesterday seeking a court order to take control of that pipeline. 
Dynegy had agreed to acquire Enron on Nov. 9, but canceled the deal last Wednesday, citing what it called Enron's misrepresentations about its financial health and a ''material adverse'' downturn in Enron's core energy trading business. As part of the merger agreement, Dynegy invested $1.5 billion in Enron, gaining the right to acquire the pipeline if the merger fell through. Dynegy now plans to take over the pipeline in eight days. 
But in its lawsuit against Dynegy, Enron said that its smaller rival had no right to cancel the merger and asked the court to block Dynegy from taking control of the pipeline. 
Yesterday, in a conference call with analysts and reporters, Dynegy senior executives struck back at Enron and provided new information about the failed merger, saying that Enron's actions destroyed its remaining credibility with investors and customers. 
Dynegy's chairman, Chuck Watson, said his company had been working to salvage the merger until about a week ago, when it became clear that a deal was impossible because of Enron's shrinking liquidity, its huge debt load and its deteriorating trading business. 
Dynegy's doubts started on Nov. 19, when Enron disclosed that it had only $1.2 billion in cash, Mr. Watson said, whereas Dynegy had estimated Enron would have more than $3 billion. The disclosure was ''pretty startling,'' Mr. Watson said. 
''This basically implied,'' he continued, ''that Enron had burned through over $1.5 billion in less than three weeks. Neither the treasurer nor chief financial officer could explain where the cash went.'' 
Dynegy officials have also cited Enron's disclosure on Nov. 19 that a downgrade of its credit rating a week earlier meant that a $690 million debt due in 2003 had to be repaid by the end of the month. Enron has asserted that Dynegy knew about the debt and that the downgrade took place only after the merger documents were signed. 
But in an interview yesterday, Dynegy's president, Stephen W. Bergstrom, said that Enron stated explicitly during merger negotiations that its debts would not be accelerated unless its credit rating was downgraded all the way to junk status -- something that did not occur until six days ago. 
''In our agreement, we had a representation that any downgrade would not affect any of their debt, unless it was downgraded to junk status,'' Mr. Bergstrom said. 
Enron's cash drain accelerated after Thanksgiving, further darkening hopes of a merger, Dynegy officials said yesterday. By the Friday after the holiday, they said, Enron informed Dynegy that it was down to $882 million in cash, and by the following Tuesday, Mr. Bergstrom said, Enron had $500 million to $700 million. 
By that weekend, the Dynegy officials said, Enron said it had worked out a new infusion of more than $2 billion in cash that would stabilize Enron's trading business. But by late Sunday, Dynegy said, the proposed infusion was down to $500 million -- far short of what Dynegy felt was needed to address Enron's immediate problems. 
People close to Enron have said bankers were actually willing to invest $1 billion at that point. An Enron spokesman declined to comment yesterday. 
Mr. Bergstrom said that he had been frustrated not just by the cash drain after the pact was signed but also by the refusal of Enron officials to let him visit Enron's traders. 
Some bankers and board members had debated whether Enron's chairman, Kenneth L. Lay, should step down to help salvage the merger, Mr. Bergstrom said. But Dynegy never sought to remove Mr. Lay as a condition of the merger, he added. 
As Dynegy and Enron square off in court and in the press, Enron's foreign investors remain in confusion. In Japan, money market funds have taken a beating because of their Enron holdings. Investors yesterday punished the stocks of the companies that manage those funds. 
Managers at the Dabhol Power project in India, 65 percent owned by Enron, said Enron's efforts to sell its stake would probably be set back. Creditors are uncertain whether Enron can proceed with a sale on its own or will need bankruptcy court approval.

Photos: Yesterday Enron dismissed about half of the 7,500 employees at its headquarters in Houston, including these two workers. (Associated Press)(pg. C8); An Enron employee wipes her eye as she leaves the Houston company yesterday. The energy trading company sought protection from creditors on Sunday. (Associated Press)(pg. C1) 
