Attorney Says Tender Offer For Enron Is 'Off The Wall'
By Lynn Cowan and Todd Goren
Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES

12/04/2001
Dow Jones News Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

WASHINGTON -(Dow Jones)- A private Illinois company that wants to take over Enron Corp. (ENE) is "off the wall" said a Chicago bankruptcy attorney Monday. 
"The party who made the tender offer either is incompetent or looking to see his name in print, regardless of the fact that it would be made to look like a fool," said Gerard Munitz, a principal at Goldberg Kohn Bell Black Rosenbloom & Mortiz in Chicago.
Munitz and other reorganization specialists said they had never seen a case where someone made a tender offer to shareholders of a company that has already filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy. But that's what Standard Power & Light Inc., Oak Brook, Ill., said it plans to do with Enron shareholders, according to a Securities and Exchange Commission filing Monday. 
Enron's shares closed Monday at 40 cents a share, up 14 cents, or 53.8%; Standard Power & Light said it anticipates the tender offering price will be under $1 a share. Enron said only that it had not received the tender offer. 
Standard Power & Light has never operated a company as large as Enron, and it's unclear whether it has ever actually developed or operated a single power plant on its own. The company was incorporated six years ago to buy and develop power plants; in June, it sold its interests in two projects, according to its president and chief executive, Richard Ryan. 
At the conclusion of the two sales, "I then took the money and retired to Wisconsin," Ryan told Dow Jones Monday. 
He recently rejoined Standard Power & Light. Aside from Enron, he said Standard Power & Light is looking at a new venture in southern Illinois. 
Ryan said he thought Enron has enough assets to effectively manage and retire its debt. 
"Of course, equity holders will have to accept lower returns for a while, but the assets are there," he said. 
In a bankruptcy reorganization, creditors are paid back before shareholders receive any money. Common shareholders are usually among the last investors to be paid, and often don't receive anything for their stock, Munitz said. 
"While there's nothing to stop someone from trying to acquire Enron's stock, why would they do so?" Munitz said. "With a company that under the best of circumstances is so far underwater that it will never pay its creditors in full, let alone have value over and above its debt for distribution for equity stockholders?" 
Munitz said normally, someone interested in taking over a company in Chapter 11 would file a proposed plan of reorganization in bankruptcy court that would be approved before stepping in and buying it. 
"That's the way any lawyer would recommend doing it," Munitz said. "Unless you're looking to have thousands of stock certificates to sell as souvenirs." 
-By Lynn Cowan, Dow Jones Newswires; 202-628-9783 
Lynn.Cowan@dowjones.com 

(Todd Goren also contributed to this report.)

